12. What is a Synonym ? Types of synoname ?

=> 	👉 A synonym is an alias (alternate name) for a database object such as a table, view,
			 sequence, or procedure.
		   It helps users access objects without knowing the owner schema or full name.

	 ✅ Why do we use synonyms :

	 	👉 Hide schema (owner) name
	 	👉 Simplify SQL statements
	 	👉 Provide abstraction & security

	 ✅ Types of Synonyms in Oracle : There are 2 main types.

	 	 👉 Private Synonym -- A synonym owned by a specific user and usable only by that user.

	 	 			🔹 SYNTAX - CREATE SYNONYM emp FOR hr.employees;

	 	 👉 Public Synonym -- A synonym owned by PUBLIC and usable by all DB users.		

	 	 			🔹 SYNTAX - CREATE PUBLIC SYNONYM emp FOR hr.employees;		

	 	✅ EXAMPLE : Suppose the DBA creates: 

	 	-- CREATE PUBLIC SYNONYM emp FOR hr.employees;
	 	-- GRANT SELECT ON hr.employees to SCOTT;

	 	✅ Now user SCOTT can run:

	 	SELECT * FROM emp; instead of SELECT * FROM hr.employees;


